If you think about it, the IN operator is really not needed.  It just adds complexity. 
For example, you can say
{code}assignee is currentuser(){code}
and
{code}assignee is in (currentuser()){code}
and
{code}assignee is in membersof(jira-users){code}
and
{code}assignee is in (membersof(jira-users)){code}
and
{code}assignee is in (currentuser(), membersof(jira-users)){code}
but not 
{code} assignee is membersof(jira-users){code}

I understand why the last one doesn't work, but really adding the "in" into all these examples is purely just aesthetic. The meaning could be derived by a parser purely by the subject of the sentence without the IN or WAS IN. Certainly by the time the search makes it to Lucene's language the IN part is lost.

I bring all this up because I have written a Javascript parser for all this in the [HP/Palm Jira Search Plugin|https://studio.plugins.atlassian.com/wiki/display/HPPSP]. When it gets down to breaking up the WAS IN (...) clause, you have to inspect each item in the list to determine whether IN applies or not. It would be easier to just not have to worry about whether to apply an IN.

Another way to look at what I'm trying to say is, just make the singular operators = and WAS also include IN and WAS IN

